Shadow Buffer
Motivation
  • We’ve discussed shadow buffers
  • But there were several problems:
    • Limited to 90° light area
    • Abrupt transition from lit to unlit
    • Aliasing
Review
  • Method of operation
    • Draw to shadow buffer
    • Draw normal scene
      • Reproject to light camera
      • Draw, maybe with shadowing
  • Our shadow buffer is just a 2D texture
Example
  • This is the kind of results we had:
Analysis
  • Square region. Looks kind of ugly.
  • Could use dot product to get location of point relative to center of light “view direction”
  • Condition now becomes:
bvec4 conditions = (
    distanceFromLight < light_hither,
    distanceFromLight > light_yon,
    distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance+BIAS,
    distance( p.xy, vec2(0.5) ) > 0.5 )
if( any( conditions ) ){
    //...shadowed...
} else {
    //...lit...
}
Result
Analysis
  • Looks better if we have soft borders
  • Intrinsic: smoothstep(a,b,c)
    • If c ≤ a: Smoothstep returns 0
    • Else if c ≥ b: Smoothstep returns 1
    • Else: Smoothstep returns 3t2 - 2t3 where t = (c − a)/(b − a)
Code
  • To compute shadow:
if( any( bvec3(
    distanceFromLight < light_hither,
    distanceFromLight > light_yon,
    distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance + bias ) ) ){
    percentLit = 0.0;
else
    percentLit = smoothstep(0.3,0.5,distance(p.xy,vec2(0.5)));
Results
Question
  • What if we have omnidirectional light?
  • We need a way to cover 360°
  • Solution: Cube maps
Cube Maps
  • We’ve seen cube maps already (environment maps)
  • We can create a cube map FBO
  • This will allow our light to be omnidirectional
Procedure
  • When we initialize light: Create six cameras
  • Here’s what I used:
//p = light position
vector<Camera> lightcameras(6);
vec3 cois[6] = {vec3(1,0,0), vec3(-1,0,0),  vec3(0,1,0),
                vec3(0,-1,0),  vec3(0,0,1),  vec3(0,0,-1)};
vec3 ups[6] = {vec3(0,-1,0),  vec3(0,-1,0),  vec3(0,0,1),
               vec3(0,0,-1),  vec3(0,-1,0),  vec3(0,-1,0) };
for(int i=0;i<6;++i){
    lightcameras[i].yon = 200.0f;
    lightcameras[i].hither = 0.5f;
    lightcameras[i].fov_v = 45.0f;
    lightcameras[i].updateProjMatrix();
    lightcameras[i].lookAt(p, p+cois[i], ups[i]);
}
  • When we create the shadow buffer, we create it as a cube map
    FramebufferCube shadowbuffer{512, GL_R32F};
  • Rendering into the shadow buffer is similar to how it was with non-cube maps except that now we do it six times:
for(i=0;i<6;++i){
    lightCameras[i].setUniforms();
    shadowBuffer.setAsRenderTarget(true,i);
    lightcameras[i].setUniforms();
    //...Draw scene...
    shadowBuffer.unsetAsRenderTarget()
}
Pass 2
  • For second pass: Need to sample cubemap using vector from light source to position we’re deciding shadow for:
vec3 L = lightPosition.xyz - worldPosition;
float distanceFromLight = length(L);
float shadowBufferDepth = texture(shadowBuffer,-L).r;
//remap from 0...1 -> hither...yon
shadowBufferDepth = lightHither + shadowBufferDepth * (lightYonMinusHither);
if( distanceFromLight < shadowBufferDepth + bias ){
    //lit
} else {
    //shadowed
}
Soft Shadows
  • In real life, photon emitters are not point sources
  • Real shadows have two regions: umbra and penumbra
Regions
  • If light treated as point source: A & C are 100% lit; B is 0% lit (100% shadowed)
Regions
  • In regions A & E: Entire light source visible, so 100% list
  • In region C, none of light visible, so 0% lit
  • In regions B and D: Part of light visible, so it ranges from 0%…100% lit
PCF
  • Commonly used technique: PCF
    • Percentage Closer Filtering
  • Idea: Instead of sampling once from shadow buffer, we sample several times close to the original point
  • Review: Recall our shadow buffer technique:
    • Let p = vec4(v_worldPos.xyz,1.0);
    • p = p * light_viewMatrix
    • distanceFromLight = -p.z;
    • p = p * lightProjMatrix;
    • p.xy /= p.w; p.xy += vec2(1.0); p.xy *= 0.5
    • t = texture( shadowbuffer, vec3(p.xy,0.0) ).r;
    • shadowBufferDistance = light_hither + t * light_yonMinusHither
  • Before we then said:
    • If distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance
      • shadowed
    • Else
      • lit
PCF
  • PCF works the same way, except we sample the texture several times
  • Ex: Sample a 3x3 grid of texels around p:
float numShadowed = 0.0;
vec2 delta = 1.0/textureSize(shadowBuffer,0).xy;
for(float dt=-1.0;dt<=1.0;dt+=1.0){
    for(float ds=-1.0;ds<=1.0;ds+=1.0){
        vec2 p_ = p.xy + vec2( delta.s*ds, delta.t*dt );
        float t = texture( shadowBuffer, vec3(p_.xy,0.0) ).r;
        float shadowBufferDistance = light_hither + t * light_yonMinusHither;
        if( distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance )
            numShadowed += 1.0;
    }
}
float shadowPercent = numShadowed / 9.0;
Results
PCF
  • Problem: This gives us only 9 levels of shadowing, which can look blocky
  • Problem: Lots of texture samples → Slower
  • We can make it faster by using jittered or irregular sampling (ex: a poisson disk pattern)
Variance Shadow Maps
  • Takes advantage of statistical sampling theory to reduce blockiness
  • Fake soft shadow edges
  • Not perfect, but simple and gives nice results
Strategy
  • Declare shadow buffer as two-channel/float:
    Framebuffer shadowbuffer{ w,h, 1, GL_RG32F };
VSM
  • First pass: Just like before, except:
    • Let d = eye space z, negated and mapped to 0…1 range
      • Use light hither=0, light yon=1
    • Red channel gets d (distance from eye)
    • Green channel gets d2
VSM
  • After rendering first pass: Blur shadow map
    • shadowbuffer.blur( 0,0, radius, 1.0f );
  • Larger blur radius = softer shadow edges
VSM
  • In theory, we should create create mipmaps after the blur
  • I skipped this step and it didn’t seem to make any difference… :-/
VSM
  • Second pass: Draw scene as before except: To determine whether point is in shadow:
    • Sample from shadowbuffer texture
    • Red channel = mean
    • Green = deviation
    • Let variance = deviation - mean*mean
    • Let d = distance between point we’re shading and light source
    • Map d to 0…1 range (0=at light camera’s hither; 1=at light camera’s yon)
    • If d < mean: Fully lit
    • Else: percent_lit = (variance)/(variance + (d − mean)2)
    • Clamp percent_lit to 0…1
    • No need for “magic constant” of bias
Results
Analysis
  • Variance shadow mapping suffers from artifact: Light leakage
    • Occurs where large discontinuities in depth from light’s perspective
Solution
  • We can make artifact less noticeable by reducing blur radius
    • But this also reduces shadow “penumbras”
  • Another way: Raise percent_lit to some power
    • We got rid of the bias magic constant, but now we have a new one!
    • Diminishes problem, but doesn’t get rid of it entirely
  • Or: Consider any shadow amount < ε to be black; remap range from ε…1 to 0…1
    • Use percent_lit = smoothstep( epsilon, 1.0, percent_lit )
Results
  • No magic, Magic of 1.5, Magic of 4
Results

ESM
  • Exponential Shadow Maps: Similar to VSM, but less data to move around
  • First pass: Draw to shadow buffer
    • Let z = -v_worldPos * viewMatrix
    • Let z’ = z but mapped to range 0…1 (hither → 0, yon → 1)
    • Output s*z’ to shadow buffer
      • s = arbitrary scale constant to reduce shadow bleeding
ESM
  • Second step: Blur shadow buffer
    • Should use log blur (see references) to avoid artifacts
ESM
  • When shading fragment:
    • Let z1 = value sampled from shadow buffer
    • Let z2 = -(v_worldPos*light_viewMatrix).z
    • Map z2 into 0…1 range (light_hither → 0, light_yon → 1)
    • Percent lit = ec⋅(z1 − z2)
      • c is an arbitrary constant to scale the shadow appearance
Analysis
  • ESM requires half as much data as VSM
  • ESM can have problems with artifacts when caster and receiver are near each other
  • And shadows become less soft as caster-receiver distance increases (this is opposite the way things work in real life)
